-{"id":"asupersync-bwd","title":"Implement benchmark suite for Phase 0 baseline performance","description":"# Benchmark Suite (Phase 0 Baselines)

## Purpose
Establish baseline performance metrics for Phase 0 primitives so we can:
- detect regressions early
- validate “hot path” expectations (avoid unnecessary allocations)
- measure cancellation/drain latency (latency-sensitive)

Benchmarks should be deterministic in the sense that they:
- run fixed workloads under fixed lab configs
- do not rely on wall-clock randomness

## What to Benchmark (Core)
### Task/Region
- spawn + complete latency (noop tasks)
- region open/close latency (empty region)
- nested region overhead (depth N)

### Scheduler/Waker/Timers
- wake cost under dedup (many wakes => one enqueue)
- timer heap insert/pop costs

### Cancellation
- time from cancel request to terminal state for:
  - single task
  - tree of tasks
- overhead per checkpoint

### Combinators
- join (2-way) overhead
- race (2-way) overhead including loser drain
- timeout happy path vs timeout-trigger path

### Two-phase primitives
- MPSC reserve+commit cost per message
- reserve+drop (abort) cost per message

## Instrumentation
To validate “zero allocations on hot path”:
- use a test allocator or allocation counters in `cfg(test)` / bench cfg
- at minimum, assert checkpoint path does not allocate

## Harness Choice
- If we want statistical rigor: use `criterion` (dev-dependency)
- If we want zero deps initially: use `cargo bench` + `test::Bencher` (nightly) is not acceptable unless toolchain is nightly

Plan-of-record: start with `criterion` only once Phase 0 kernel is working, because toolchain/CI constraints may evolve.

## Determinism
- Bench inputs use fixed seeds/configs.
- Bench output is compared by trend, not by exact nanosecond equality.

## Acceptance Criteria
- Benchmarks exist for the categories above.
- Bench failures/regressions are actionable (identify which benchmark regressed).
- Bench suite does not compromise library purity (no stdout in core; benchmarks may print summaries).

